<h4>True buttons</h4>
<p>True buttons use either the &lt;button&gt; or &lt;input type="submit"&gt; HTML tags. They are typically used for things like form submissions, or to trigger some kind of action on a page. For consistent user experience, the styles that can be applied to real buttons are limited.</p>

<button>Button</button>
<button class="alt">With .alt class</button>
<button class="warning">With .warning class</button>
<button disabled>Disabled Button</button>


<h4>Links styled as buttons</h4>
<p>To style a link as a button, add the .button class</p>
<a href="#" class="button">I'm a link!</a>

<h5>Style Options</h5>
<p>Links styled as buttons have a number of classes that can be used to alter the style, shape, color, and size of the button. Default buttons are filled, round, blue, and small. There are no classes for these defaults. Add any of the following classes to the &lt;a&gt; tag to customize your button links. You can use any combination of these custom classes to produce a large number of possible button styles.</p>

